notes.author: author(s)
notes.description: Critical Web Design is a broad category that includes internet art, creative activism, and cultural production. Works must be networked or used online or with computers in public, be intentional in their production so as to cause users to think deeply about some tech or related issue. This document contextualizes these using various themes, categories, technologies that epitomize these types of works.
notes.AI: Uses or addresses artificial intelligence, machine learning, smart devices (see also bots)
notes.animation: Incorporates or takes up time-based work, moving graphics or text, other animated forms as its subject
notes.anthropocene: The current geological period, characterized by ongoing and human-created environmental impacts
notes.anticorporate: Of, about, against corporations, and corporatization of daily life and relationships (such as 'collective instruction')
notes.archive: A collection of documents on, within, or relative to a subject or object
notes.bot: Software or automaton that runs on its own
notes.censorship: Blocking, banning, manipulating the communication of content, or the subject thereof
notes.collection: A list, exhibition of, or compilation of links to CWD works (see also, archive, index)
notes.color: Works about color or that use it in a novel or significant way
notes.culture-jam: A form of d√©tournement that is specifically anti-advertising, anti-corporate
notes.data: Works that are about data and information collection, processing, storage, retrieval, examination, etc.
notes.deceptive-design: Design that deceives users in order to manipulate their behaviors, also referred to as 'dark patterns'
notes.design: Design or its practice is the subject, or methodology
notes.detournement: A rerouting, hijacking or subversive intervention
notes.diagram: The work contains diagrams, flowcharts, processes, systems, etc.
notes.documentary: Works that present an examination using facts and information. Also see journalism
notes.dynamic: Works that are connected such that the data, interface, experience, etc. is variable, and based on dynamic information or scenarios (above simply relying on a database or changing the layout updates)
notes.encryption: The subject or methodology involves security, encoding, encryption of information
notes.education: Pursues the subject, goal, or supports education, pedagogy, teaching
notes.extension: Browser extensions, bookmarklets, and other hacks
notes.forms: The work relies on web forms to work or is about input somehow
notes.game: Challenges users (players) through achievable goals and feedback
notes.generative: Works that generate new content, forms, ideas, using randomization, and other techniques etc.
notes.glitch: About, embracing, presenting, or creating unintentional disruptions in technology
notes.grid: Uses grid for presentation or addresses grids somehow
notes.hacking: Modifications of an existing system, protocal, software, etc. towards critical ends
notes.humor: Works that incorporate humor in some way
notes.index: A list or collection of links or references of a specific area. An archive collects the object, an index organizes and points to the references.
notes.interface: The work is about, is novel in its approach, or plays with HCI, interfaces, mouse, keyboard, and/or other inputs
notes.maintenance: Provides a service, support, help, or care in some novel way
notes.manifesto: Presents text describing what could be, or how they intend to frame modes of thinking
notes.mapping: Provides indications of location using maps, scale, visualization, etc.
notes.math: Math, computation, counting, numbers, quantities, etc. play an important role
notes.meditative: Provides an experience that is meditative, contemplative, spiritual even?
notes.narrative: Uses plot, stories, and other devices that describe time and events
notes.nature: About or references to the biological world
notes.overidentification: Following and idea to its ridiculous end in order to critique or examine its supposition
notes.participation: Users have the ability to affect data within the project, which is stored and then influences others' experiences
notes.photography: Uses or somehow address photographic, video, or film processes or media
notes.play: An experience or information in the work that involves or evokes a playful response
notes.poetry: Text, poems, and other literary forms that present ideas yet through finely tuned and minimal content
notes.politics: About political ideas, or involving political acts
notes.power: Uses prediction, assumptions, illusions, or other techniques to enable or address power
notes.randomness: Incorporates random values somehow in the work
notes.remix: The work intentionally reuses or appropriates ideas or media into new forms
notes.resource: Collection of free assets, etc. for, of, about CWD
notes.self-sustaining: The works somehow support themselves through financial, or other means
notes.social: Creates social space, or is about social networks
notes.sound: Uses or about audio, sound, music
notes.subvertisement: Spoofing or parodying advertisements or marketing 'anti-ads'
notes.surveillance: Addresses issues of privacy, surveillance economy, etc.
notes.tactical: Attempts to insert ideas into new spaces through intentional actions (also see political)
notes.text: The content is primarily written, composed of text, or about the subject of textual information
notes.typography: Focus on the representation and manipulation of text characters, ascii, identity
notes.usability: The work is about or addresses somehow usability, accessibility, inclusiveness
notes.utility: A tool, created to be used or somehow provides a utility
notes.visual-poetry: Also referred to as concrete poetry
notes.visualization: Data or information transformed into new, more easily recognizable (or not) forms for understanding or emotional effect
notes.XR: Uses or about augmented reality, virtual reality, or related methodologiesAR/VR/etc

data.name: opensea.io/collection/web-2023
data.author: Jan Robert Leegte / Superposition
data.description: Web (2023) https://opensea.io/collection/web-2023 by Jan Robert Leegte and Superposition, is a generative cross-linked network of 1000 web pages. The entire network of pages can be explored through the links contained in each page, using any page as a starting point. In addition to each generated and unique composition, which includes its color palette, interface composition, and even favicon, each document is "on the chain", meaning the code for the generated network could be accessed from any single blockchain record. "Web is not a utility, but an expression of the machine."

data.name: exhaustingacrowd.com
data.author: Kyle McDonald, Jonas Jongejan
data.description: Exhausting a Crowd (2015) https://exhaustingacrowd.com/ by Kyle McDonald is a web application that depicts detailed security camera footage upon which website visitors can add annotations synced with both the imagery and the time code of the video. The crowdsourced text laid over the 12 hours of repeating footage from various sites offers curious commentary which perfectly balances the opposing forces of surveillance vs privacy, looking vs being seen, and control vs pleasure that defines our information culture and public spaces.

data.name: Safebook
data.author: Ben Grosser
data.description: Ben Grosser creates browser extensions that modify the content you see on Facebook and other social media websites to question how those technologies influence us. His Safebook extension removes all content from Facebook, leaving an empty shell to remind users of the importance of their free labor to the company's bottom line. Likewise, his "Facebook Demetricator" extension removes the metrics on posts that drive participation and engagement and focus on gamification of interpersonal communication. As with all browser extensions, these modifications are performed using Javascript, but only within the browsers (client) of users who install the extension. Find these and others on his website https://bengrosser.com

data.name: clickclickclick.click
data.author: Studio Moniker
data.description: The website, https://clickclickclick.click (2016) by Studio Moniker tallies the untold and revealing information that can be gathered as a user hovers over a button, clicks, or drags their cursor across the page. Rather than feeling in command, the user begins to feel watched and controlled as their every action is documented and fed back to them in an ongoing text. This critique of gamification employed across web and application design relies on our knowledge of the increasing manipulation and remarketing of human attention. Yet it presents an alternative that is not only clever, enjoyable, and educational, but public, immediate, and free to use and appreciate by anyone with a networked device.

data.description: In C&D Grand Prix, the art collective MSCHF created 8 shirt designs that used companies‚Äô logos without permission. They then sent letters to the companies to see which would be the first to send a C&D ("Cease & Desist") notice demanding they stop using the logo. Meanwhile, they sold the shirts, allowing anyone to wager on which company would raise the specter of legal repercussions before the others. Whoever picked the winner also received a hat with their shirt. The results are published at https://cdgrandprix.com

data.name: lowtechmagazine.com
data.author: Low-tech Magazine
data.description: Low-tech Magazine https://lowtechmagazine.com is an online publication that questions the value of technological progress, describes the potentials of often forgotten tech, and promotes sustainable energy practices. Unlike the mind-numbing megawatts required for server farms and data centers used by Amazon, Instagram, and TikTok, Low-tech focused on efficiency in their design by removing advertising and using a static site generator (Hugo), allowing them to power their server using a single 50W solar panel.
